76561198066253605,Recommended,518790,31905459,Posted: 22 May,all,SABINA,"Amazing Hunting/Hiking Sim, Unfairly Underratedhttp://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=918934092Fantastic hunting simulator. Large open world. Beautiful graphics. Immersive audio and weather systems. Realistic mechanics. Optional quests and rewards. Hidden lore and loot to find. More than fair price range, with additional free content being added. More additional content in the form of dlc. Some bugs, but nothing game-breaking or to detract from the overall gameplay in my experience thus far, and the devs are working on it. The devs have honed their skills in previous games to bring us this one. It's not their first rodeo.So, all this begs the question, why the low review rating? I mean, what's not to love here?http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=919246069If you read through many of the ""not recommended"" reviews, they generally read something like this: ""Fantastic game! But..."" or ""I love this game! But..."" or ""Best hunting sim ever! But..."" and so on. The ""but"" is an almost universal gripe about a tiny, optional content dlc that reviewers think should have been part of the base game. They consider the dlc a sign, contrary to initial projections, that there will be micro-transactions on the horizon. So the result we see here is an ugly trend in the community to try and bully the devs into compliance, with negative reviews. The negative reviews on the game are almost entirely reviews of the dlc, not the base game. This is unfair, and akin to journalistic terrorism in my opinion. As a result, it has put the devs and mods on hyper-defensive in the forums. The low reviewer rating that has resulted from the negative reviews will cause less people to buy the game, in turn lowering the revenue for the devs, thusly diminishing the likelihood of quality updates and additions in the future. I understand that the reviewers are trying to force the devs to make positive changes to what they see as a poor business model, but the actual effect that it has, in reality, is only to hurt the game and the chances of getting the improvements they want. I'm all for freedom of expression, but there are forums for communicating with the devs, positive ways to get the message acrosss, without attacking a game that they admittedly love because they didn't like something about one dlc. The next content addition has been announced and will be free. But has that made the reviewers change their reviews back to positive? Of course not. Hence the often learned lesson: never negotiate with terrorists.http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=922747560theHunter: Call of the Wild is a great hunting simulator. The gameworld is big and beautiful, immersive and awe-inspiring enough to double as a pleasant hiking simulator. I will keep coming back to this game when I've had enough of all the linear shoot-em-ups out there. If you are interested in hunting sims, have a hunter's eye that can track movement even when the object is well camouflaged, if you have the patience to stalk your quarry through the driving rain, love the tense thrill of lining up that perfect shot, and after it all enjoy a gorgeous sunset vista from atop a watch tower... if you can get past the reviewer rating (seeing that they are not actually game reviews, but reviews for one dlc) and give this game a chance, you will not regret it.Recommended for screen archery inScreen Archer's Guild"
