76561197998128953,Not Recommended,518790,31961703,Posted: 25 May,all,jimslade,"This game has beautiful graphics, but it's just not a good game. I am sorry, because I really wanted to like this and invested 30 hours into it until I decided it's enough.As I said, the graphics are great, sound is good, but not awesome, This basically is a stealth game where you have to develop a good situation awareness. It's about footsteps you hear, animal calls - the whole game crys for heaphones all the time. Why you don't have proper binaural sound but only pretty shabby stereo is acutally pretty mind boggling. Other than that, some sounds were obviously recorded in real nature, with some noise in the background. But I guess that's okay and somehow adds to the game's authenticity.What's makes the game fall apart is the gameplay or the absence of any. Okay, I get it. This is a hunting sim. It's not your casual shooter, not your fancy Thief like stealth game, it takes time, you have to be patient, I get it.But this game just does not ask for any real strategy.There is a mechanic that you're making more noise depending on where you walk - but I honestly never found out how that worked. It seemed pretty much random to me.Also there is no real way to plan or strategize. You can't really provoke a certain behaviour from the animals. If call them, they stop and listen, maybe come closer and then either walk away again or they see you and run away.You can mark them FarCry-style, but only for a few seconds. You don't have any chance to circumvent them or something like that before you don't know where they are anymore. With bigger animals like deer and bisons this is ok, because you wont lose them so easily. But hunt a fox or a roe deer and they get out of sight pretty quickly.So the only real strategy is this one: You go into the woods until you find some tracks. Sometimes they are fresh,so you follow them. Sometimes you hear an animal call and you follow it. You'll eventually spot an animal, take out your gun and shoot it. To make things easier, you can buy animal callers to attract your game. That's basically it.Oh, you can build lookout points, too. But then you sit in the lookout point for a long, long, long time without anything happening. Yeah, it's a hunting game but maybe a fast forward button to accelerate time would have been nice here. See, I'm not playing anything when I sit on my lookout point and wait for an animal to come by. And waiting will be long even if you got to know certain animals will pass by at a certain time of day (you'll find need zones to get this kind of information). In fact, you'll be a lucky ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥, IF they come by at all. So, just don't build lookout points. (Yeah, you have to buy every single one of them.)You can also do missions. These range from trivial (I once completed one by accidentally pressing the E-key) to just friggin impossible. I quit this game after I repeatedly tried to hunt that damn fox with that stupid bow. These little fellas have ears that hear you across at least 50 meters. They are clever and always cautious. And they are small so they hide perfectly in the undergrowth and higher grass. With your ♥♥♥♥♥♥ standard bow you have to get close. Very close. I invested several hours into that stupid mission - now I won't anymore.It wouldn't be so bad if I could just pimp my equipment, buy a new bow, maybe a new sight, some fox spray so he can't smell me. You know, handy stuff like that which is actually in the game - but blocked behind an xp barrier. So get some stupid binoculars, I have to be level 20 or 30 or something. I hate mechanics like that! Why can't I just buy that ♥♥♥♥ing better bow if I have the money for it? It doesn't make sense! ""No, no, you have to be an epxerienced hunter to use this spray can, my padawan.""And that too wouldn't be so bad, if progress would be at an acceptable pace. But it isn't. Maybe I'm stupid, but I invested 30 hours into this game and I'm level 13 now. 13 is nothing. 13 in this game means a little bit better than your starting equipment. After 13 hours of play!! And no, I am notallowed to buy the better bow or the fox spray.Why is progress so slow, you might ask? Well, it's a hunting game and it takes some time to hunt stuff. I just hunted that damn fox for an hour and got zero xp and zero money for it. Your average deer gives something about 100 to 150 xp. You can get more for harder and rarer species or for specimens with high trophy ratings - but it's more or less a lottery whether or not you'll find them. So, with 150 xp per kill you have to kill about 15 specimens to get from level 13 to 14, f.e. You can assume that you'll need about 15 minutes for a kill - at least. You can do the math yourself. And that's the playstyle that incorporates stupid, mindless grinding. If you want to properly play the game, explore the word, find good game etc., double or triple that time.How much time would I have to invest to buy my better bow and the spray so hunting that stupid fox would be a bit more fun and I could end this story mission? A few hours. Maybe six, maybe more.And that's not fun.I'm sorry, I really wanted to like this game, it's brautiful to look at, but your game designers need a kick in their butts."
