,Not Recommended,518790,31464075,Posted: 30 April,all,Iridium,"This game is absolutely beautiful. The scenery is stunning and very well done. This is also all wrapped up with fantastic sound design. Headphones are really mandatory here, partly to help you hunt your quarry, but also to be fully immersed into the lovely sound design that went into it. The hunting mechanics are solid, if at times a tad frustrating for impatient folk like myself. It all comes together into quite an experience.Do not buy this game.It seems nice up until the point where you realize that the experience is desperately lacking a few things, and those things stand out big and bold as stuff that no self-respecting game tester would have let slide. Easiest example of this is the complete lack of transportation. Early on you're given a mission that's a significant distance away. You could fast travel... but only between outposts, and only after you've discovered them, and that only occurs after you've jogged 30-45 minutes, or more across a map, wheezing away the whole time. There are roads everywhere, sure. But no transportation? No ATVs, no bikes even? That wasn't a miss, that was a conscious decision. The inclusion of tents as the first DLC feels very much like that as well.And let's not pretend that this is a misstep on the part of the publisher. Don't forget that the first iteration of this game required a subscription, or very expensive DLC, to permit you to hunt anything beyond exactly one type of deer. Frankly, many of the mechanics in this edition feel like they were prepared to be DLC-enabled anyway: equipment that you need to progress (sort of, it's much more difficult without it) is level locked ealy on, and requires in-game money to buy. You can sense that there were ""XP and Credit Boost"" microtransactions ready for this before they decided to pull it.To be clear, I'm not anti-DLC. It can be fantastic for many cases. If this had been a complete game I'd probably be more interested in DLC that added in new regions, for instance, or added other not-basic game mechanics.As lovely as the game seems to be on the surface, the business model here seems to be predicated on frustrating the player in very basic, obvious ways,  to ensure future DLC payouts. This is the second most cynical, ridiculous way to squeeze more money out of dissatisfied players... and this game's predecessor made use of the first most."
