,Not Recommended,518790,35481212,Posted: 4 October,all,Alex,"theHunter: Call of the Wild - Review after 30 hours of gameplayTL;DR Skip to the bottomThis game feels like an early access game hidden beneath the guise of full release discussed in depth below.theHunter: Call of the wild [First Impression]theHunter: Call of the wild here-in referred to as CotW gives you an amazing first impression with it's stunningly beautiful graphical fidelity. The ambience of the soundtrack will make you feel totally immerssed in this hunting simulation style game. The wildlife feels, at first glance, realistic enough with their calls of mating, warning and pathing. It gives you just enough tutorial to throw you straight into the game to understand it's basic mechanics without overloading you, however, just too little to teach you how to play the game properly.theHunter: Call of the wild [Maps]Both the Lake and Hirchfelden maps will take your litterally hours to traverse around the borders of them with a variety of areas such as mountains, rivers, lakes, plains, and forests to explore for animals. So whether you are taking pictures with your ingame camera or hunting you'll have no shortage of beautiful terrain to walk through to do so.Overall I'd rate the maps a stunning 8/10. While these maps are quite beautiful there are only 2 maps at the time of this review. If you spend any real amount of time in the game, you'll learn them like the back of your hand. They are not gigantic maps but they are big enough.theHunter: Call of the wild [Progression]It seems to be a growing trend in newer titles to have some form of progression system. Now while this works perfecly well with their leveling, skills and perks system it falls flat on it's face with weapons progression. To unlock higher end weapons you must use lesser weapons and their optics in harvested animals. Meaning you do not get the experience for your shots unless you track down your animal. It makes sense from how they implemented it but not why. There should be no need for progression on weapons. If I have the cash I should be able to purchase the weapon of my choosing regardless of the power of the weapon or view distance on the optic.Overall I'd rate the progression system a solid 5/10. It's completely average with no real innovation though it does needlessly lock weapons behind a seperate experience system which to me is a negative.theHunter: Call of the wild [Stealth]CotW does have an intricate stealth system that works very well. You make noise as you move through grass, shrubs, bushes and trees making stalking prey a nice challenge for bow hunters and other close quarter hunters. It feels good to sneak up on your prey and take it down from stealth. Hiding in trees, bushes and tall shrubbery will also reduce your visibilty to animals making it an effective ambush location if you choose your spot well.CotW does NOT have camoflague clothing that works with the stealth system. This means even if you buy the camoflague clothing, for a high price I might add, it does nothing but change how you look to other players as you play from a first person perspective. So unless you want to play CotW barbie dressup edition clothing does nothing for you and that is a real shame. If I'm hunting in real life, which I do, I buy camoflague to increase my chances of bagging that trophy whitetail. There is already a visibility reduction statistic built into ground blinds that could be attached to camoflague clothing. To me this is a simple and much NEEDED fix to make immediately.Overall I'd rate the stealth system a very good 6/10. It's above average and does everything you'd expect it to. I've docked this from being better for the lack of real hunting camoflagues. A characteristic found in the much more venerable title of the same franchise, theHunter Classic.theHunter: Call of the wild [Weapons]CotW suffers from a serious lack in variety of weapons. You have 2 shotguns, 3 pistols, 3 bows, and 7 rifles. It's really quite pathetic. This compounded with the fact that each weapon of the same type has the exact same effective range is a complete joke. Every single rifle has the same effective range of 150 meters, that's it. As a military veteran of the united states army I can quite easily tell you that their .338 rifle has an effective range of over 500 meters and has confirmed hits at over that range. It's unacceptable at best. Weapons also suffer from poor audio balancing. When firing the .357 magnum pistol for the first time while wearing headphones at an average or above average volume level it will give you quite the startle. Where as the .223, .243, .270, and 7mm rifles all have a good balance of sound. The ammunition choices seem acceptable at first glance until you shoot a .270 round into a white tails lung and it fails to come out the other side or penetrate both lungs. I've had 1 shot using the soft tip ammunition penetrate both lungs in easily over 100 rounds fired into lungs. In real life soft tip expansion rifle rounds more often than not go clean threw the animal. They don't stop because they hit the shoulder bone either unless you're hunting something above the rifles weight class like a bison. The accuracy stats on these rifles is all over the place. As an example one of the lever action rifles has over 800% better accuracy than a BOLT ACTION .338 LAPUA MAGNUM! Have these developers done any weapons research whatsoever? Apparently not.Overall I'd rate the weapons a lazy AF 1/10. There is no real weapon variety. The audio balancing is poor. The same range on all weapons is BEYOND lazy. The lack of realistic bullet penetration is pathetic and the accuracy ratings on some of these weapons is mind boggling inaccuracte.theHunter: Call of the wild [Animal Artificial Intelligence]CotW suffers from some of the WORST animal AI I have ever seen in a hunting game. As a former game developer and with a little exploration I was able to come to a logical conclusion.|||The following statement can be construed as hearsay as I do NOT have access to the games coding.(I believe the AI to be run on a pathing map placed below the real map that the players walk on. I have seen this blank map and have reasonable suspition to believe that the cause of some of the horrible pathing of the animals can be attritubed to this.)|||Sooner or later you'll find animals that seem to walk completely in place without moving. Other times you'll find them running blindly into the same tree and sometimes for over 60 seconds. It's quite bizzare to watch an animal you've just shot at run at full speed, going nowhere, into a tree. I have also witness ""sinking"" animals where animals occasionally clip into the terrain. A bug common in theHunter series and still seems to be affecting the later titles as this bug is common around hills in both classic and CotW.I've watched animals return time and time again to an area in which I have fired a rifle, shotgun and pistol in harvested the animal and watched them return to me without callers. We had believed animals to avoid hunting pressure areas but that does not seem to be the case 100% of the time. In fact it happens so frequently that I've managed to at one point harvest 6 animals within 50 meters of where i first shot 1, then the second, third, etc.Overall I'd rate the Animals Artificial Intelligence at a 5/10. It's workable but could use some improvement.theHunter: Call of the wild [Final Verdict]While the game runs great on it's maximum settings and has very high quality ambience the game suffers from illogical design choices and lazy programming. The lack of working camoflague in a hunting simulator is unacceptable. The animals AI is servicable but needs work. The stealth system works good enough and is acceptable. The weapons system is a complete and utter joke.Overall I'd rate it 5/10. I'll be on theHunter Classic until it's fixed."
