76561198137294466,Recommended,518790,30039816,Posted: 19 February,all,Alterego_Loki,"First Steam review so bear with me...The Basics: A hunting ""simulator"" that drops you into a massive map with a gun in your hand a somewhat helpful voice in your ear. No real setup, just cuts you loose with some very basic and in my opinion decent enough tutorial messages. You could follow the missions that pop up on your huntermate or ignore them. As far as I can tell, nothing is gated behind the completion of any of them. So as soon as you start you can do as you please, unlock outposts, lookout points and other assorted collectibles around the land. Not to mention trying to land your first, of many, kills.Graphics: Game is gorgeous as hell. Dense forests that give way to open fields, lakes and rivers carving through the hills. Its just a treat to look at. Not to mention the animals are very well done also. Though if I'm honest (and that's the point right?) the animals could maybe use a second albeit small touch up. Nothing a non critical eye would notice. I can't help but feel like this is the way game maps were supposed to be designed from the beginning. It's so great walking through the bushes and branches hoping that you can get a shot on a deer you can barely makeout in the distance. There are a few low texture and blurry bits but I was too awestruck to notice until the five hour mark.Sound: The sounds are great and not great. Mixed bag. Mainly some are too loud. Some are recycled leading to confusion and some are kind of odd. The rain is an example of excellence. I absolutely love the rain in this game. It truly feels like I am standing in the forest in a storm, and when thunder occurs, I nearly jumped from my seat. Example of bad sound is when for instance, a rabbit takes off from a few feet from you. Not only is it loud as balls, but it makes the same sound as your polyester jacket scraping tree branches. Sounds like this being repeated led to me constantly wondering if a deer responded to my calls, a rabbit got startled, or I'm just molesting a tree. Another positive though, the voiceovers are quite nice. (at least so far)Gameplay: It's an incredibly simple premise done quite well. You go into the forest and shoot animals. Main drive is to bag the biggest and best you can. It's a very addictive cycle for myself. The game makes it very easy to decide whats worth you ammo. You get experience for better kills ie right tool for the animal, quick kills, and better trophies. You also level up your skill with a particular weapon or tool type which opens up new variants at an oupost. There are perks and skills that allow you to alleviate the difficulty in subtle and so far non game breaking ways.ETC: The main gripe here with most people is the grind. It takes a long time to begin unlocking things. Me personally though, the gun you start with is more than sufficient and games like these aren't about racing to the end, it's the journey along the way. Other issues are that when playing with a keyboard and mouse it's currently impossible to sneak effectively. No matter the stance you make hella noise moving through any kind of underbrush. And yes, there are reports of quite a few assorted bugs. Missing ammo, scopes not working, animals glitching out. I haven't personally experienced these but I feel for those who are. I trust that given a little bit of time, the dev team will iron these things out and build upon the solid foundation that they have laid. Even the early days of the Hunter classic were an ugly time.TLDR: Buggy, beautiful, and fun as hell.When it comes down to it, this game at its worst is miles better than any other hunting game at it's best."
76561198060586973,Recommended,518790,30202002,Posted: 26 February,all,maciora,"Gameplay:Its not Call Of Duty in the Forest, where bears on steroids, 50 feet tall attacking innocent topless girls in mini skirts, and u save them - (btw I would love this kind of game) - this is slow paced, hunting simulator. My last hunt was tracking black bear for like 20 minutes, and then hit it from 250 meters in the head.It really was like real life hunting - you have shot statistics after hit, where did u hit animal and the score. Its really interesting. I can suspect there will be more DLCs like Alaska with Grizzly bears and stuff like this - which will make this game only better.Graphics are great, and you really have feeling being in the forest, moving slowly tracking your prey - if you like, slow paced games, where you have to think a lot, a truly hunting simulation - it is game for You."
