76561198067697636,Recommended,518790,33397410,Posted: 9 July,all,Dim67,"Beautiful hunting game that's hit and missThere are a very games that manage to recreate the beauty and complexity of nature as well as TheHunter Call of the Wild. Games like Farcry, Tombraider, Ghost Recon come to mind with each their own style. But for me CotW captures more than pretty graphics; and that is feeling. A sense of immersion, of actually being there. A sense of lonelyness. The lighting, the amazing colors of the leaves on the trees, the reflection of a waterpuddle, the heatshimmer over a cornfield, the swaying of trees and bushes in the wind, the distant overhead humm of an airplane. The game also manages to create a sense of curiosity: ""I wonder whats over that ridge. Or behind that bend in the road. Whats over there by that water?"" All this is very well done and thought out.But at the same time the game also has some major flaws in that same design: while the re-use of the same type of trees, bushes, rocks and grass is not that bothersome and still manages to create a beautiful environment, the re-use of the exact same models for outposts, lookout towers, abandoned barns and hiking shacks soon becomes a distracting annoyance. These locations where you can re-stock your supplies and buy new items or rest to advance the time, are very static and feel very empty. Some of those locations offer even no interaction at all.The hunting mechanic is very well done, with realistic animal behavior and animations and your presence in the environment accurately impacts how the wildlife reacts.There are a few options in the menu that allow you to adjust what is visible in the HUD, such as blue outlines around spotted animals for example, but its still hard to find a good middlepoint between Arcade and hardcore simulator. There are too few adjustible options in my opinion.The mission-system is also not very strong in this game. There is a somewhat decent storyline to guide players towards new areas to explore and animals to hunt, but some of the missions are tedious or outright annoying. The ""take a photo of two bears"" type missions can be a serious headache and being sent out to down a red fox with a bow, way before the player is able to unlock the small animal Caller is very frustrating.The slow pace of the game unfortunately soon becomes a grind. Prices in the shop for equipment and ammunition are outrageous and earning experience points for Skills and Perks takes forever. Some of those skills or perks have minimal or no impact on actual gameplay which is not very rewarding.The game is still actively being developed with new patches or DLC very few weeks or so. The fact that some items like an ATV and tents and blinds that should have been part of the base game were added in as a paid DLC, and that sit not very well with the majority of players.These patches are desperately needed because the game still has a ton of bugs like graphic glitches, sounds cutting out, missing items from the gameworld or inventory, wildlife spawn issues etc. etc. Eventhough the game is playable the buglist is huge.But all in all this is a very enjoyable and pretty virtual world to walk around in. I hope the developers focus on what needs to be fixed in the current game, before adding any new stuff."
