76561198027057922,Not Recommended,518790,30690872,Posted: 23 March,all,NeoTheLizard,"This is a game in which changing from one map to another in singleplayer requires you to delete -ALL- character skills, leveling, bought items, discoveries. Essentially any and all progress made throughout God knows how many hours. This was 29 hours of unlocking that I need to do all over again. I♥♥♥♥♥♥you not. Why, Expansive Worlds, why?For as many good things can be said about Call of the Wild, something seems to have gone awfully wrong throughout development for it to have this sort of inexcusable disregard for basic functionality. Keep in mind that this is a game that features fairly complex stealth systems, somewhat complex animal AI, and so on, yet needs months worth of patches to get an ""Exit to menu"" button, which still hasn't been implemented,-in which debug menus show up for a split second when clicking on at least one of the buttons in the main menu,-in which animal call markers sometimes appear and sometimes not for no apparent reason,-in which there are no search filters, password protection or direct connecting in the server browser,-in which most menus are a pain to navigate due to poor design choices,-in which one ammunition stack always weighs the same regardless of its size,-in which there are red dot sights for shotguns mentioned in one of the skill menus despite the fact that there are no available red dot sights for shotguns and other discrepancies in the information provided to the player,-in which you can't buy more than 1 unit of ammunition at a time,-in which you can buy a seemingly infinite supply of the one ammo type that's free,-in which you can't interact with any of the unlockable hunting towers or land marks in a game you didn't host,-in which there at least weren't any animations for simultaneously walking and using animal calls the last time I checkedand yeah, I just discovered that unlike its predecessor your character info isn't tied into your account or anything, but into the singleplayer match you need to start the first time playing. And since there are two areas to choose from, you'd better host a multiplayer match if you want to play the other map because you otherwise need to wipe your only save slot, because why not? Keep in mind that it probably takes weeks or months of playing in order to unlock the later skills, perks, and equipment, so why does the save system work in such an awful way?Somehow, this is a recurring problem with Expansive World's games. There's always some insanely basic stuff that doesn't work or works in some astonishingly awkward ways that defies long-established conventions for no reason whatsoever. Having fun with this is task which currently demands a very high level of patience and tolerance for severely lacking functionality and polish, and I really, really don't understand how this trend can continue to persist within the games of a developer I'd think was experienced enough to make a keybinding menu that wouldn't completely break the control scheme if tampered with. This was fixed in an earlier patch, but yes, it was something that happened too. Call of the Wild is not a bad game if measured purely by its intended design, but this sort of garbage persisting is inexcusable and by now i feel pretty bad about supporting it in the first place."
