,Recommended,518790,34163096,Posted: 11 August,all,TheAmpleSam,"As of writing this review I have yet to complete the 'Story' mode.GameplayA lot if not the majority of the base game will include you walking, crawling and stalking your choice of game, whether that be Roe Deer, Wild Boar or any of the other animals in the wild. You have the ability to track your target animals and get information off of their traveling, eating, sleeping and other habits, also if you have shot, but not killed an animal you can find blood splatters that will tell you if they are vitally wounded or not making it more interesting to track down your target. Running is in the game, but often it is best not to use if you want to avoid alerting and scaring away potential animals. Though it is useful especially if you are just exploring new terrains. The stealth aspect of the game works well and will force you to be patient in order to successfully get a kill. There are useful tools you can use including scents to cover your natural human smell as-well as animals 'calls' to attract whichever animal you are hunting. There is a 'story' mode in single player where you will be asked to do tasks including take pictures of animals as-well as just shooting animals (sometimes with a certain gun) in particular locations around the map. You can disable these story mode messages in the options which is a nice feature if you just want to freeroam. Early on you will want to find an outpost so you can resupply and have a place to fast travel to as this is very important. the outposts can be found from just exploring and often are easier found if you find a lookout post to get a layout of the land. At the beginning of the game you will have only one rifle some deer attracting devices with not much other weapons/gear and you will have to level up to get more options for guns and equipment. There is a perk system aswell as a skill tree you can level up for whatever you play-style is. There are two maps to choose from and both have different animals to choose from to hunt. As-well, there is a multiplayer mode with up to 8 players that is accessible after you get your first outpost in single player. While this mode is fun, it is inconvenienced by the fact the host of the server will be free to fast travel to whichever outposts they have traveled to in single player so long that they have discovered the outposts. The problem is that if any other players join the host and don't have certain outposts unlocked in their singleplayer that the host has unlocked in their game, the nonhost player will be unable to fast traveled and be forced to walk to whichever outpost the host fast traveled to. This problem is remedied by either just walking to all outposts in your single player world before considering playing multiplayer which will take considerably long considering the maps are rather large. Alternatively you could purchase the ATV dlc, though this feature feels like it should be included in the base game rather than a premium item that is only accessible through a micro-transaction.GraphicsThe game was made using the Apex Avalanche Open World Engine and it looks great regardless of which graphics settings you use. While using higher graphics settings all of the vegetation is thick and bustling and the scenery truly pops and gives a great sense of immersion in the game world. If you are on a lower end machine though, you can turn down a great amount of the post-processing effects as well as vegetation and shadows and still be left with a very visually pleasing game. What I really appreciate in their graphics setting menu is that they tell you what level of a performance impact all the settings do for you so you can gauge what type of performance you would gain from turning down some settings.Audio/SoundsThe audio is where this game shines a great deal. The sounds you will experience are so immersive. Every little leaf, twig and rock on the ground will give a satisfying sense of you being on said item. The weather as-well sounds are very impressive, whether it be a little wind or a horrendous thunder storm. All the sounds in this game sound perfect. When in multiplayer as-well if your hunter friends are firing at game far from your location you can hear the booming echoes of their shots echoing through the terrain. All animals have their own unique voices and if you are lucky enough to get close enough to listen to them you will truly appreciate the clarity in the animals voices. The only thing you may get sick of relatively quickly is the in-game music. While after initially hearing the beautiful songs you will indefinitely appreciate how smooth and well fit they are in this game. You will soon hear them repeat very frequently and will likely just disable them as they do become quite a distraction the more deep you get into the game.StoryYou're a hunter who has free roam to two reserves including Layton Lake District, a map modeled on the North American Pacific Northwest, and Hirschfelden, a recreation of a European farmland type area. Your main objective is focused around tracking and killing animals in order to gain more points to get better gear to hunt with.My opinionWhile there are some problems such as not including the atv with the base game and it being a micro-transaction, aswell as some minor nuisances in multiplayer such as the fast travel problem and some of the animals in multiplayer servers seemingly having an infinite amount of health which really takes you out of the game. I do believe this game is great especially for the patient minded players in mind. I do believe if you have or even have not hunted in real life you will find this game to be a great attempt to capture the essence of that experience. I recommend this if you don't mind tracking animals for long periods of time, or luring game to you in hopes of getting that perfect shot. If you are looking for something faster paced and action oriented then this game likely is not for you."
76561197961090434,Not Recommended,518790,34350926,Posted: 19 August,all,Hyperion,"This is a good concept.  The game itself is a lot of fun.  If it had been developed by an experienced, competent design team using industry standards, it would be absolutely amazing.  I don't want to give this a thumbs-down, but I cannot in good conscience recommend this game unless you enjoy single-player games that lack both a ""pause"" and a ""save"" function.The world in the game is beautiful, and the game is challenging and fun to walk around and track animals.  There are a few missions/quests, enough to give you something interesting to do, but you still have the freedom to walk around on your own, and to take targets of opportunity.  There is also a process for unlocking better weapons and ammo as you increase your score, and this along with the need to earn money in-game by making kills, gives you rewards to keep playing.However, there are several serious problems with this game.  There is currently no pause feature.  This sounds like a minor omission until you realize that real life often does intrude on gaming.  Maybe you have dinner in the oven, or you have to take medication, or family members call, or you have to use the bathroom, or any number of things.  With most (single player) games, you take for granted that you can hit Pause and do your business, and come back to the game and continue.  Not in theHunter COTW.  Even if you hit the Esc key to bring up the menu, even if you're browsing through the in-game help or changing settings, the game continues to run and things continue to happen around you.Another problem is that the game does not feature TrackIR, even though its predecessor did, and the devs have no plans to add this capability.  Instead they have integrated something called Tobii Eyetrack.  Virtually every other game that calls itself a ""realistic simulation"" uses TrackIR, so most of us who enjoy this sort of game already own TrackIR, and it would add a lot of immersion.However, one of the biggest problems with this game is the save feature: there is no save feature.  The game saves automatically, which is nice...until you lose power in a thunderstorm while playing, and the next day you find that the game doesn't recognize the save file even though the save files are very clearly still on your computer, the game only gives you the option to start a new game.  Oh, and to make it even better, if you decide to start a new game, it overwrites the save files already on your computer.  That's because there is no ability to save-as, no ability to have multiple save files.After 15 hours of play, I am not going to start a new game.  Unfortunately, after 15 hours I am also not eligible for a refund.  This game is nice, but the developers are clearly amateurs.  I don't mean that as an insult, I simply mean that they do not adhere to basic industry practices and standards.  This is sad, because it is a very nice game, but unfortunately incompetent developers are one bug that cannot be fixed."
