76561198010199565,Not Recommended,518790,30293800,Posted: 3 March,all,Mannschaft,"**UPDATE** They just patched this game yesterday and this morning. The patch claimed to fix a long standing bug that would kill you whenever you loaded the game up. I have NEVER had this bug happen to me. Then they release a patch that they say fixes this bug. I load up the game and for the first time ever I am killed upon loading the game. I'm sorry but these devs are a joke. Every single patch that comes out seems to either break as much as it fixes or doesn't fix what it says it fixes. Most of their patches have day of or day after patch hotfixes. I STILL CAN'T MAKE THE GAMEPLAY SETTINGS SAVE. Every time I claim a kill or open the menu to look at my map, all of the gameplay settings are reset to default. It has been like this since the day I got this game. So sick of these devs at this point. They're either lazy or incompetent or both.I'll try to be as fair as possible with this.The Good1- Amazing graphics and great optimization. Even with my rig that was built in 2011 (GPU upgraded since then to 970), I can run the game on max settings and still get 40+ fps.2- The sounds. Everything is crisp and authentic. The ambient life is especially well done with a staggering array ranging from crickets to different birds like loons and kill dear (it's a bird). I especially love the wind through the trees sounds. It makes me feel like I'm at home and the rain sounds are good but lack a bit of beef.3- Tracking is pretty fun and an added bonus here is that you can turn off all visual tracking aids if you're feeling particularly masochistic. I nearly couldn't find a coyote in a bed of flowers even with the aids on.4- MASSIVE maps. You may only get two of them for now but these things can take you over 2 hours to walk from one end to the other. These are beautiful environments.The Bad1- Volume. Some sounds are just totally out of whack volume wise. Heaven forbid you get within 50 yards of a rabbit because if you do your ears will be graped with what sounds like dragging something across a gravel road. Walking through water is excessively loud as well.2- The UI. Repeatedly have to hit some buttons to navigate the menu. It's a pain in the bunghole to deal with.3- The map. The stupid thing opens to a random point and zoom level every time you open it and it's as stupid as can possibly be. Sometimes it opens zoomed out all the way. Sometimes zoomed in all the way and nowehere near your current point. Obvious bug I expect to be fixed sooner than later because it's so♥♥♥♥♥♥♥irritating so I'm not terribly worried about it but it needed mentioned.4- ""Nothing to do"". This is extremely important because right now the only goals in the game are to level up and spend skills and perks to unlock abilities you should have because realism. There is no trophy system that I can find. No way to go back and relive past kills or have trophies to look at. The only point of the game right now is to use your weapon more to unlock the next weapon and kill more things to get more money to buy the weapon. What does this mean? It means the game is a kill fest. There's no limit to the number of animals you can take home to feed the kids so you end up just killing everything that moves because you need the weapon skill to unlock the next weapon and you need the money to buy it. I once let a doe go because I had just gotten done killing 5 does. After it walked off I asked myself why I let it go. There is no reason whatsoever to let anything in this game live.5-Being harder to see in fog and rain are actually skills you must unlock in this game which reaches maximum potato levels. Sorry but you don't need training to be harder to see in these atmospheric conditions. Fix it.6- Wind only sometimes masks your sound.7- Rain never masks your sound.8- Kill data diagram is badly implemented. I'm talking about the xray image of the animal you shot with bullet penetration data. It's all blue and white so the whole thing ends up getting washed out and it's hard to see where anything is at. I definitely can tell where the lungs are at, but where is the heart? I don't know I can't see it because it's all white.9- Sometimes fall damage. Sometimes not. Just slid down the side of a mountain at top speed taking no damage and then it launched me off near the base and I flew forward like 100 yards and fell like 50 yards and didn't take a single bit of damage. Wat?10- Fog. Everywhere there's fog. News flash! The sun burns the fog away by mid morning. I shouldn't be walking around through a hazy wood at noon, especially with wind. Your light shafts and god rays are beautiful but cmon guys.11- There shouldn't be animal noises during heavy rain/wind storms.12- No blood spray/spurt from animal upon shooting. No gutting the animal. No bullet hole or blood on animal despite spraying 1 gallon of blood out of its lung. I consider this a mortal sin at this point considering how realistic everything else is.13- You don't exist. When you wipe your phone your hand moves so far forward that you can see where it disappears. You are a floating pair of hands and that is also why you commit the greatest mortal sin in this entire game. YOU CAST NO SHADOWS. This is ridiculous. As tragic as loading up a $60 AAA title and realizing that mirrors don't have reflections. Also, being in environment shadows does not affect your visibility and neither does night time.The Neutral1- No bullet time. I know I know....not realistic. But I love bullet time and I've been spoiled with it from other games for years. Would be fun to have especially considering the only point of this game is to kill everything that moves whether or not you would take that animal in real life.Am I enjoying this game? You bet! But there is so much wrong with it that I couldn't in good conscious tell a buddy hey you should get this. Some of the bugs are rage enducing. Some of the features make me seethe. No blood or wound on the animals is as stupid as doing a hand stand and farting even though you have diarrhea.I have high hopes for this game and will continue to get high and have a super relaxing time playing it but just be warned about the negatives because in my opinion they far outweigh the positives at this point."
,Not Recommended,518790,30096937,Posted: 22 February,all,Knut,"I am deeply confused - what's this game supposed to be?Sandbox game? Hunting ""Simulation""? Arcade Hunter? Open World Adventure?First of all: Endless, purposeless tranquilityif you enjoy walking up a beautiful virtual hill for 15 minutes without any further purpose but to reach a viewing platform, then this game is totally for you and you should just ignore my review.Second: Oh my god, dem bugs.Others have mentioned it before, but this game is far from being ready for release. For early access the level of bugs and issues would have been acceptable, but still better to call it an open beta.The main problem I have with this, is that ExpansiveWorlds (Avalanche Studios) has a long-standing track record of releasing unfinished content and often never polishing it to perfection even way later. This is true for basically every update theHunter:classic received, but especially for theHunter:Primal - a game that was sold in some kind of beta-state (especially content-wise) and never made it any further.Third: Blimey, dem graphics!The game looks awesome! The vegetation, the scenery, the lighting, the animal models, the animations (well, besides the players hands, what the frog am I doing? Running in the praying mantis karate base pose?) - all looks terrific and stunning. The way you leave a trail of flattened grass behind is just cool. Ok, it looks like you're a Mafiosi that just dragged a concrete-cuffed rival to his favourite dumpster lake, but hey, it's still a cool effect. A shame that the graphics are the only outstanding part of this game. I am more willing to overlook less-than-perfect graphics than flawed game design or mechanics.Last but by no means least - the real review - what is this game meant to be and why did they get it all backwards?So you got theHunter:classic, a massive open-world hunting game with plenty of content and great game mechanics. It just suffers from a meanwhile rather dated graphic engine  (fair enough being already 8 years old) and a microtransaction-based business model that has met plenty of criticism. Yet the cash-cow seems still lactating, as they are still keeping the game alive.So what to do to lead theHunter into the future. Develop a successor and kill your cash flow of the old game? Much better to produce something slightly different that recruits new customers, fascinates your old clientèle and still doesn't stop them from spending on the old one. Much better idea indeed. If you're able to pull it off, that is.So why not make an open world hunting game like the hunter that still has a story line. Red Dead Redemption hunting themed, basically. Nice idea.But then why they got it all backwards? Why does the actual hunting feel like you're mowing down the imbecile cousins of some majestic animals you dreamt of hunting all your life? The actual hunting is no challenge at all, you just need to be in the right place, and the animals will be easy to harvest.The ""story line"" (in brackets, as I am not sure yet, there's any red line through the story - it might just be random bits) on the other hand is slow as a sloth. A couple of hours in and I haven't even proceeded much in the tutorial story line (it is supposed to be a tutorial, right?). All I did is wander lengthily through a beautiful landscape getting sidetracked by some dull hunting while trying to get to a lodge or view point or camp.I feel a good hunting game with a story line should be exactly the other way around: extensive, to some extend challenging hunting embedded in a faster paced, enthralling story line. That'd be an interesting cross-over game between an emersion-intense hunting game and a hunting-themed arcade/adventure game. This game is exactly the opposite. It got real dull real quick for me, and I am a sucker for a good hunting game.I'll probably wait for a follow-up of theHunter:classic. Or maybe even a similar product by a competent competitor that might be released in a rather finished state - one should be allowed to dream big."
