76561197970429546,Recommended,518790,31614132,Posted: 7 May,all,The Spirit of Jazz,"I've been a shooter more or less all my life, my father taught me how to shoot with a crappy .177 air rifle when I was about 6 and I've been hooked ever since. As such, hunting games have always been something I've craved, so when I saw The Hunter: Call of the Wild up on steam for £30, I couldn't resist.I'm going to address the negatives first because I want to end this review on a positive note, given that I am recommending the game.The DLC. Yes, the £2.79 tent DLC. I know a lot of people have been laying into the game for this and I can understand why. I played The Hunter Classic for about an hour, then I dropped it because I didn't like the payment model. I know of people who have put over a thousand dollars into Classic and quite a few who have put hundreds in, so I think the reaction to the tent DLC is understandable. However, I also believe a lot of the negativity this game is getting comes down to people being annoyed that the game they put hundreds of dollars into is now available, in full, for £30, albeit a slightly reduced version of the game (the online is nowhere near as sophisticated), but every bit as fun and atmospheric at least.The simulation aspect. This is where my main grip with the game comes from. On the one hand, the game takes the hunting aspect very seriously. Damage modelling is excellent (I know, I hit a red deer in the leg and it limped off before I quickly delivered the coup de grace) and the tracking and calling mechanics are top notch. Some people say this game makes tracking too easy. To them I say visit the options menu. From there, you can tweak the tracking to make it as easy or as realistically difficult as you want to. The ballistics are well modelled, to a point, and this is where the game lets itself down in the simulation aspect. The accuracy statistic. It is, to be blunt, nonsense. What should be the most accurate rifle in the game and the go to weapon for long shots (it's the go to weapon for snipers in both the US and UK militaries) is in fact the least accurate rifle in the game. I am of course referring to the .338. With an accuracy rating of 10/100, it's a joke. I'm baffled as to why the developers have done this. In fact, I'm baffled as to why each weapon has an accuracy rating at all. Just model the ballistics of each calibre as accurately as possible and the ""accuracy rating"" will sort itself out. The accuracy with bows is not what I would expect, although I say that as a bow shooter and a pretty decent one at that. The accuracy you'll get out of the bows is probably about on par with what you would see from somebody who's had an hour or two of practice, having never shot with a bow before. This is a difficult one to balance I guess and it does stop you from taking ""pot shots"" at long rage with the bow. It's best to think of bows as a close quarters weapon, which they are in real life anyway, but I was a tad disappointed when a shot I took from about 15 yards ended up hitting the deer in the back leg, rather than the lungshot I was going for.Bugs. There are a few of these, although they mostly relate to the UI. There's a very irritating bug where a blank tutorial hint will stay on the screen until you quit the game and restart (quitting to the main menu doesn't fix it!). After you know your way around the game, you can thankfully turn these hints off which stops the hint from appearing and thus fixes the problem, but still. Also the directional indicator for the tracking mechanic will sometimes send you in the opposite direction that it should, although if you're paying attention to the animals footprints this isn't too big of an issue. The game also occasionally crashes when resting at an outpost, it has done this twice in 64 hours of play so nothing too drastic, but does need sorting. These are the main issues I've encountered and nothing else comes immediately to mind. None of them game breaking, just mild irritants.The animal models are all the same as far as I can tell. Every buck/stag has the same wonderful looking rack, there are no 2.1's here, and they could use some more variety in both the size of the animal for both male and female animals and the quality of the rack for the males.So, what do I like, no love about the game? Well, pretty much everything else.The visuals are beautiful. From the dense foliage, the swirling mists that get blown by the wind to the sunlight/moonlight breaking through the trees and shimmering off the leaves, it really does do everything it can to make you feel like you're really there. The weather effects are great, although I was a little disappointed that my weapon didn't get wet when it rained, but that's just nit picking really, but overall the graphics are stunning.The sound effects are top notch too, although the audio mixing at night could do with a little tweaking, the crickets can be deafening at times. The animal calls and their movements through the foliage are excellent and you can pinpoint their locations just by listening. The rifle reports are great, as is the twang of the bow and the shnick of the arrow as it finds its mark.The story missions are fun, well voiced and there's plenty of them, some of which are quite challenging (like shooting a fox from 167 yards!).Overall, the audio/visual presentation creates an unrivalled atmosphere and a real sensation of ""being there"". I've played most hunting games, from the original Deer Hunter series to the Cabella's (Their Big Game Hunter: Pro Hunts is well worth checking out too, for a slightly more ""arcade"" experience) but Call of the Wild tops the lot for sheer atmosphere and immersion. It's the absolute best hunting game I've played so far, by a long way. I hope the developers continue to update the game, fixing the bugs and providing more content (more animal models please devs!) because they've got an absolute winner on their hands here, no doubt.If you like hunting games, even in the slightest, then The Hunter: Call of the Wild is a no brainer. It's £30. The same price as a takeout for 3 people. Just buy it already, really. You won't regret it."
