76561198015467747,Recommended,518790,34123935,Posted: 9 August,all,ANTI_POGUE,"I've been playing The Hunter series since 2009 when it came out... The original had some really nice animals, arguably better weapons but the paid subscriptions killed me off eventually.This new COTW is great, I am an avid hunter and outdoorsman in my personal down time - this almost gives me a bit of an escape from reality at home with headphones on, slink around the hills for half an hour, hunt some deer / elk / moose / bears etc then close it down.Like some people have said, the deer are unreasonably good listeners! They can hear you from 400km, which is brutal. There are a heap of animals around but you generally only catch a glimpse of them running off in the distance between some trees unless you're basically crawling everywhere.The Quad Bike DLC is awesome, but has changed the game a lot. I like them to get around and go to all the lookouts / unlock all the outposts but other than that they make hunting a waste of time, everything nearby clears out. Tents are convenient, that's about all.The firearms, are fairly crap... They're unfairly balanced, don't do realistic damage, you can go prone but still have offensively useless muzzle / sight picture control... The external and terminal ballistics of the ammunition are light on making you often wound and then be forced to track even female fallow deer for kilometers sometimes which is rubbish.This game could REALLY DO WITH SOME more modern, practical rifles - eg a Bolt Action 300WinMag / 7mm Rem Mag / 6 or 6.5mm Creedmoor or 260Rem for the Elk and other deer. .300RUM / .338LM / SAUM etc for ELR hunting and maybe a couple of Semi Auto .223 / 300 Blackout for foxes / pigs etc... The hippies and european naturalists get their hooks into the weapons and get into a tiff which is frustrating, they don't want to add any reasonable firearms (listed above) because it doesn't fit their demographic back home, get over it. Add them in, if you don't want to use them then dont... For everyone else, they're another option.In summary, I love this game but it's a bit one dimensional still. The damage should be increased proportionally, the firearms should be modernised to reflect the rest of the western world. Probably my favourite game."
76561197991906240,Recommended,518790,32737311,Posted: 24 June,all,Jewish Jesus,Finally a walking simulator I can get behind.
,Recommended,518790,30067568,Posted: 20 February,all,[κρά]Goose,"theHunter Call of the Wild.. what a game. It's the perfect hunting game for people who just want to relax, enjoy the scenery and then take down a nicely lined up buck putting their name on the leaderboards to top their friends!Seriously this game while it has it's flaws is like one of those games you hate but you keep playing because it's fantastic at the same time. You can lose so many hours in this game just from walking around and finding loads of beautiful location in which you can spam the screenshot key and post all over your steam profile. So into the nitty gritty! The review-[ Gameplay ]-The gameplay is awesome, the animal tracking, wind, callers, weapons, clothing and scents. There's a decent amount of equipment to keep you entertained for a while!Now the wind has to be the biggest feature of this game, simply sneaking up to an animal quietly just won't cut it anymore if you're upwind of an animal. Unless you don't have a scent sprayed all over you.. You're going to struggle to kill it. It will smell you before you even see it. Sometimes they throw a warning call, that could be your saving grace to bag it. If not, reposition so you're no longer upwind, get downwind and call them towards you. The sound you make also can scare animals off, If you're walking through a bush it makes more noise than walking through grass as you would expect, so planning your route whilst getting set-up is essential to get the big scores!Gun play, while you can shoot any animal with any gun you do lose score by doing this, if you're going for a big buck to try and top the leaderboards, don't go running in with a 7mm unless you getting Bison or something. You have the make sure you using the correct rifle and ensure the 100% Trophy Integrity which adds onto your final score. The sounds of the guns firing are really nice, they sound similar with small differences... but. They sound awesome!Perk/Skill system, compared the theHunter Classic, CoTW (Call of The Wild) has perks and skills, as you play you gain XP, level up and you can then unlock skills and perks, this helps you hold you breath longer, gain more information about the animal you've spotted - such as weight, potential score and this helps down the line to track your animals too. So you can really tailor how you prefer to hunt and then buy the perks which benefit you.-[ Sound ]-Overall the sound of this game such as effects, wind. rain, lightening, animal calls. They're really good. Whilst there are some small bugs where you can't locate a call if you're in a menu and then exit. Also sometime calls don't display so you physically cannot locate them. It's pretty uncommon that this happens. The wind sounds are spot on although sometimes really loud when in a blind/tent and the same goes for the rain. I would love to see a weather sound volume slider so we can keep the sound effects high, just lower the weather sounds.-[ Multiplayer ]-The best part! Hunting with your friends is awesome. The multiplayer is pretty stable. Never really had a lot of issues with it either apart from the small desync with animals but changing the time in-game simply seems to sort this out. If you are hunting with a friendas much as you'd love to roll around together and hunt together it's not practical unless you switch rolles, so a caller/spotter and then the shooter. If you're both looking to shoot you'll have to sync your shots. Which when you land two kills, is really cool! Hunting on your own in a MP lobby would be the best way to go, you can still see what they kill and the score they recieve so you can still have competition. Which makes the game that little bit more fun!The downside to Multiplayer though, If you have any tents placed around a reserve, if you're not the host, they will not be there when you join, only the hosts tents/blinds will show. Which can be slighly annoying but it just means getting your friend to set-up in close/similar locations.-[ Hunting Pressure ]-Hunting Pressure is a feature that has been added into this game to stop animals constantly vacating hotspots, so this pressure would deter animals to walk/sleep/feed/rest in these areas due to the recent harvests in that area. The way to remove the pressure from your hunting area is simply to hunt somewhere else. The way the hunting pressure works is that it has a limited amout that can ""placed"" on the map. Let's say for example the limit is 20. You go around a reserve get 5 harvests, move another 10 and then another 5. You would then have hunting pressure scattered around other areas within the reserve, but your original location would be fine to hunt there again. So it forces you to move about and explore the reserves to benefit you as you gain more XP for exlploring and finding new things with these beautil reserves!-[ Conclusion ]-I Highly reccomend this game, it's fun, relaxed and a fun casual game which you and a few friends could easily lose a few hours to. I'm a bit annoyed you have to pay a small amount for the DLC (Tents/Blinds & ATV) I feel like these should have been in the base game but other than that. Great game, loads of fun!"
