76561198158217061,Recommended,518790,31778425,Posted: 15 May,all,AdmiralTigerclaw,"How does one describe what seems to be a freeform, open environment hunting game?In a word: Frustrating.To be fair, I'm not a hunter.  I'm only a moderate firearms geek, and I was looking for something that I could play as a 'relaxed shooter'.  That's what I got.  No twitch reflexes, no tea-bagging online players, no insane aimbots that can pick you off in an eye-blink's reaction time from half way across the map.  Just, something that gave me the satisfaction of finding and shooting moving targets with the relaxation of not having to worry about winning matches, or any other bits of shooter game culture.I picked up this game knowing it was going to thrust me into simulated hunting conditions, maybe with pointers, maybe not.  I walked into this knowing tracking was going to require patience, and good kills were going to be worked for.I was right, and I enjoy it.  Even when the game is frustrating with a half-hour long chase for a shot that only caused minor injury to the animal, I find myself relaxed, but alert and thinking.  And learning a little.The game sports a wonderful environmental engine that immerses you in the gameplay world, placing you in an absolutely colossal area that takes hours to traverse by foot.  You may have looked at screenshots that show pretty landscapes, that's what you get.  Keep in mind the various landscapes are also shot from, at the time of this review, one of two primary maps.But you're not here for screenshots, you're here to hunt.  Like I said, I'm not a hunter.  But I get to experience some of what it's like to BE a hunter, albeit with some helpful HUD overlays (which can be disabled if you so desire), and a virtual 'Huntermate' GPS phone device that seems to operate on an RTG battery (Never recharge your phone again!).  Also, I'm not bogged down with licensing fees, hauling a heavy carcasses back to a truck, or regulated kill limits.  I load up, I stalk, I shoot anything I want, and I call it a day (or night).  No muss, no fuss.I've burned away hours of free time, averaging 20 minutes between animal takedowns and enjoying shots ranging from surprise buckshot, to 300+ yard love taps.  All at my own pace.  No quotas, no time limits, no pressure.The game includes a semi-RPG ish earning system, giving you skills, perks, and money over the course of your hunting to purchase gear and improve your in-game avatar.  So far, it's pretty simple to grind with, so long as you aren't impatient about it.  The animals look nice, if a bit dumb at times, but are actually a bit of a task to reliably approach for good shots.  Not the best AI in existence, but I don't exactly expect sapience.The game IS however full of bugs at this time.  The interface is clunky, the map interacts with the scope zoom settings, and even some of your tools in the game don't want to play nice at times.  Mostly, these don't get in the way too much, but for many of you who aren't tolerant of buggy release practices rampant among independent developers these days, you may want to wishlist this and wait.  Luckily, the devs seem to be moving constantly, even if nobody can agree on what the Dev's priority should really be  (Releasing a paid DLC while a savegame wiping crash bug is still being reported is a bad PR move in anyone's books).But if you're patient, tolerant, and want a casual shooter hunting experience with the freedom of an open world sandbox, don't be afraid to pick this up.  Heck, if you want, this game even makes for a good 'sounds of nature screensaver' since there are no  time pressures to speak of.I look forward to promised additional features in the future, and the cleanup of bugs."
