,Recommended,518790,35252201,Posted: 27 September,all,DoctorVapor,"I can sit for hours playing this game and never tire of it.  Stalking game will keep your heart pumping.  You never know what is around the corner, down a valley, or behind the trees just up ahead.  This is not a fast paced game, you need patients.  Animals will not come up to you waiting to be shot.  Stalking is fun, but I like to sit in the bushes and call my targets to me before the harvest.  This game is totally worth the price.  Yes, there are a few bugs, but it's nothing that is going to annoy any normal adult.You also need good senses to play this game.  Most targets are heard long before they are seen.  Using a headset will let you know what direction the animal is coming from.  Sometimes the animals strike back.  I've been mauled by a bear, and run over by elk.Check this game out.  I don't think you'll be disappointed."
,Recommended,518790,31838991,Posted: 19 May,all,Blightholtz,"In contrast to the original theHunter this game can be classed as an arcade hunting game. Sure, you'll be doing A LOT of walking in order to get to the look-out points and the camps, but you'll be having a wonderful view while doing so.I really like this game. The graphics are absolutely stunning and is really what caused me to buy it on top of the classic theHunter.However - there are a few things that kind of break the deal for me:- It's very hard to determine the distance to an animal's footsteps. They're very loud already when you first hear them, and the animal could be over 100 meters away but the sounds makes you think they're right in front of you. Would be nice to actually determine how far away they are if you don't see them.- The UI is still kind of clunky and doesn't feel like it's been worked on a whole lot. The feedback when you move around the menus is kind of lacking.- A game with linear progression like this one shouldn't have ""New game"" on the main menu as you rarely want to reset your progress unless you're right at the beginning and want to start over with a fresh load of ammo. When the game launched ""New game"" didn't reset your progress and instead let you think that you were simply starting a new session with your previously played/leveled character. After the first patch that was not the case and I lost about 10 hours of exploration. (say your little brother decides to play on your character and selects New Game, that will reset your entire character. New Game or Reset Profile should only be located in the game options or similar so that it can't be selected by accident.)- Multiplayer won't let you explore the game as much as single-player. The host of the game is the only player allowed to ""discover"" new locations to be able to fast-travel there at a later time. This kind of defeats the purpose of exploring in multiplayer if you're not the host.- In comparison to theHunter Classic I find it hard to know if my hit is going to be a vital one or not, you can be on point with a double lung shot or a heart shot and the animal will still run away and give you a quite low bonus for hit location. I guess distance to the target will lower the impact of the shot, but it just feels less fun that in the original game.Overall I'd say this game is a 7/10 as it has quite a few bugs that will impact your immersion. Let's hope that future patches will straighten those out and improve the gameplay experience even further."
