76561198131321037,Recommended,518790,31431550,Posted: 28 April,all,Jokster1911,"Ok, so I have played around 80 hours of this game. While currently everybody is mad as can be about the new paid dlc, I have no problem dropping $4 for it. ""But it is going to be just like the old hunter, micro transactions and all"" you say. Maybe, Maybe not. I personally never could get into the old hunter classic and it was for that reason. It would be sad if this game went that way, but I don't think it will. Here is why I think that. This latest dlc, while not much, didn't cost much either and it is a one time pay deal. The hunter classic was microtransactions that in some sense expired...frankly, when I pay for something, I want to keep it around for longer than just the next three months of my ""membership"". The new content also doesn't make the game necessarily more playable. Sure, it adds some ease to a few things (that I greatly appreciate), but it doesn't open a whole new world of possibilities like paid for content in the hunter classic. Would I have rather had this newest content for free? Absolutely, but as someone who has done coding and the like as part of my education and work, I have an appreciation that creating a game takes a ton of work and somebody has to pay for it. While I do wish that some content that should come standard in the base game, especially content like tents, should be free, I also don't think that paying a total of $34 for the game and its current dlc is crazy, especially when many games half as good as this game are going for the same if not more. Granted, it does have plenty of bugs and more paid dlc will add up, but the devs are actively fixing those bugs and adding features that people are asking for. It isn't as much or as often as people want, but I have respect for what it takes and understand you can't do everything all at once or make everyone happy. Simply put, this game has its issues but is currently in a very playable state that is very enjoyable. As someone who has spent plenty of time actually hunting in real life, this game is as close as it comes to feeling like you are actually out hunting. It's a relaxing experience and visually stunning. So complain about the bugs, complain about the dlc, but recognize that even the current paid dlc is nothing like the hunter classics business model and has no way of becoming the money sucking machine that game is. Still, the devs have families to feed and bills to pay too, so if paying for a little dlc content for a game that has so much potential as this is what it takes to do that, count me in. If you don't want to do that, nobody will make you pay. The base game is still there and very enjoyable regardless of any of the dlc. And no, nobody paid me to write this review."
