,Recommended,518790,30423939,Posted: 10 March,all,Crafted,"TL;DRIf you are patient, enjoy wonderful scenery, leveling up really slow but like to have a goal that takes forever- then this is your game. It's wonderful to look at, but graphics are better in the gameplay-trailers- Which I find a bit misleading.Besides that, it's all about being patient and taking your time.It's not worth it's full price, but DO buy this if it's on sale.-----PLEASE NOTEI played this only on Hirchfelden Reserve and the review is based on SingleplayerThe Storyisn't important and it's no problem straying from your given tasks. Not only is it optional but you don't get pressured into doing anything at all. They mostly sound like friendly requests, and that's what it feels like as well.They do get more challenging the further you go. In terms of challenge, this goes for aquiring equiment, shooting challenging pictures and game.I didn't really concern myself with the quests, but they do maintain a certain aspect of interest of the game. Both visually and gameplay-wise.You do unlock lore by discovering/visiting places in the game. As since the reserves are based on real places,- the lore you discover is just as real. It's easy/interesting reading and you'll have something to do while waiting for an animal to pop up.Performance and GraphicsIt's just a whole-lot of wonderful scenery and beautiful landscape to take in. If you keep moving from place to place- you never really get tired of the visually striking environment. For some reason, I have experienced multiple FPS-drops on different places. I don't know why but it's barely noticeable.Animals ranging from bears and hogs to deer and rabbits- they all look fairly good looking and behave accordingly. Animal reactions to your presents and actions are quite realistic. Both you and all animals leave a trail on the ground, pushing bushes and grass aside to leave a mark of where you've/they've been. Details like these make it look and feel just so good.Besides the fantastic graphics that some would mistake for real life, it's a downer when you are at the corner of a big cornfield watching for a fox or a red deer- that the drawing distance falls off. Beyond 100m, objects like corn and rocks gradually disappear. There are windmills east of the reseve. If you watch them from far away - these do not have blades on them.My guess is that this is a camouflaged option of optimizing the game's FPS and balancing it with draw-distance. This reminds you that it's a game and kill the realism of it.GameplayAs mentioned above, there is a draw distance in the game and this is actually a problem for a achievement that tell you to hit a animal from 400m. Because at approximately 400-405 meters, the animals disappear from your screen. If you move closer to it, it reappears (about 380-390m). Beyond 350 meters, animals no longer react to gunshot sound either, and both of these factors can kill the thrill of the hunt.I've encountered a few other problems during my travels.I'm just gonna list some examples:* Track-highlighting and animal outlines gradually stop showing when transition from day to night. Reappear once transitioned to day again.* Animals get stuck in trees, rocks and other obstacles while running. Easy but boring kills do occur.* Fast traveling sometimes remove explored animal-need-spots, like drinking spots or places they sleep. Uncertain if this is intentional.* Rain does not show through riflescopes.* Sound indicator rarely correspond to the given sounds you make. Sounds that sound noisy actually isn't. When standing still on certain places- like in a bush or next to a tree but look around you, you generate alot of noise but it doesn't show on the indicator.* Loud sounds like thunder or powerful wind does not decrease/cover the sound the player make.DO NOTlet this scare you! It's the small things that bother the most picky persons that hunt for both game and details. The gameplay itself if wonderful and intense.When you hunt for anything particular and stick to a spesific game, that's when it starts getting seriously fun! Find tracks, estimate where it is, move slowly so it doesn't see you, thinking of the wind direction to avoid it smelling you- and so on. Once you hear it calling out, closer and closer, your heart start pumping faster. If you are lucky, it's walking your direction and you can hear it rattle the leaves and bushes. Rain dripping on your clothes and dense vegetation that decreases your visibility in the foggy forest start to feel extremely real at this point. All you can do it sit and wait with your rifle aiming it's direction until it shows it's feet or antlers. It's noisy, but everything feels more quiet until you take your shot. Even I got scared of my own shots multiple times.I shot it just where I hoped it would, but it's running away. I start picking up the trail while reloading the rifle. Blood splatters indicate a vital hit and it's bleeding alot. just 3-5 minutes later, I find that beautiful creature and harvest it.Leveling, points, perks and mapIt's a REALLY slow process to level up, gaining perks and skill points. I don't know how it works, but I think it's like that you get perk points from lvl X and skill point after next one. When exploring, you can find collectables like antlers as well. These increase your XP and is a good addon to modestly increase the fun-factor of exploring.Trackhunting, discovering new places, spotting animals and hunting them is the way to earn XP. If you are bad at hunting, then you'll have a hard time leveling up.Perks increase spesific weapon-usage like the rifle and skill points increase your overall skills as a character. Skills have alot of variation, but I feel the perks lack alot more options per weapon.The map is big. Really big. It pinpoints locations and points of interest for you to discover and it's actually fun exploring it. Alone or with friends, you can place markers on the map for you to follow. Those markers will also tell you how much time it takes to walk there and the distance to it from your current position.The map is sadly not as detailed as I would prefer. The problem with this is that small details of the terrain do not show on the map, and doing a precise marking of something is hard to do.Pros:* No DLC's! Good job with that!* Not too bad arsenal of weapons, lures and scopes. I guess you could have more but I don't care.* Slow-paced.* Extremely big map and LOT's of hunting grounds* Beautiful-looking game* Fantastic sound-effects/quality* Intense moments happen alot when tracking down your game, making everything really exciting* Perks to increase e.g. tracking skills. This system feels realistic in terms of knowledge and experience you gain from hunting and harvesting.Cons:* Slow-paced. Sometimes feel like nothing ever happens (this can be a good thing!)* Stressing to find games to hunt and KoS- kills the joy of the game and makes it boring.* Leveling up is based on kills, harvesting, spotting new places and building places to hunt. It takes a LONG time to get a high level.* You are stuck with limited equipment and won't be able to aquire more unless you level up.* You can get stuck and hurt yourself on objects, rocks etc. When crouching, you can't climb as well as when you are standing- meaning hunting in close-quarters near steep ground end up like if it's a invisible maze around you.* ""Applying"" changes to resolution sometimes does not work for some reason.* Player-markers, track-highlightings and wildlife appearances needs work as since they glitch/get stuck/don't appear after long-time traveling or transition from day to night. The only way to fix this is by fast-traveling or restarting the game.I highly recommend this game to everyone.It's slow paced, rich on details, and have alot of joy for hunters. I dare say that it's close to the best hunting-simulators there is."
