,Recommended,518790,30833271,Posted: 30 March,all,kiggaxwut,"Edit: After a few more hours and some more content updates, I guess I felt like altering my review. I think I was probably a bit harsh in my previous assessment. The ATV allows you to quickly zoom around the map and pick up outposts that might have taken ages to walk to. It does a great job of scaring away wildlife so you can't abuse it and get easy shots (buffalo are another story, but I mean come on, they're huge). The tents and blinds dlc allows you to save and fast travel to multiple sites around the map, adding a better variety of places to quickly hunt.Animal pathing and AI seems better, or at least more consistent. I haven't seen a bugged animal in over 15 hours, and it seems like it's actually more rare to find things unless you're taking your time and using your binos religiously. More immersive, and more rewarding. They finally made a quit to main menu button. Excellence. Most of the UI/map bugs are patched but I still get that annoying bug where the map just opens up to a random spot. Also, I still sometimes get that weird 180 degree turn right after shooting my rifle. I can live with these things, at the end of the day.I haven't touched much of the multiplayer side of things in a long time, so I can't comment on that. But all in all this is a fun game that I really enjoy playing and would recommend to others, even with its faults.----=-=--=-=-----Wow, 80 hours already. I think this is also my first Steam review.I enjoy theHunter COTW. At the core it is a hunting simulator, and in that regard it performs somewhat admirably. The landscapes in both playable maps are expansive and beautiful. The game engine really brings out the beauty of these hunting grounds whether it's a clear summer day or moonlit foggy night. Seeing the jagged antlers of the buck you've been intently tracking for what seems like hours shimmer in the sun while it trots within the tall foliage is quite the sight to see. The sun's rays sometimes glow through the trees, creating an ambience that causes you to stop and just take it all in.Through numerous patches that have come after the game's release, the game is in, at least for me, a playable state. As mentioned in many other reviews perhaps these bugs should have been ironed out before release. I won't get into that debate as it seems to be the industry-wide norm. Bugs are minimal now, animal pathing and AI seems to be working more reliabely (though with some major faults, such as herd behavior). I haven't spontaneously combusted by walking between two rocks or two saplings in a long time. Sure, there's still some issues with terrain and how the player/animals interact with it, buggy/misplaced things such as grass hanging in the air, etc. With a map this expansive there are bound to be some issues and animals will eventually get stuck. This is part of the process and is something I can live with. However, due to my aforementioned herd behavior mention, if an animal as part of a herd does manage to bug out on a rock and get stuck, the rest of the animals will circle voilently around it until it dies (or you get trampled). This can lead to some funny/fruitful opportunities but as a hunting simulator it greatly detracts from the immersion.Multiplayer is bare bones minimal. The single-player questing system is absent in the multiplayer version, instead replaced with competitions you can start with other players. These include hitting an animal in the heart first, bagging 3 fallow deer trophies, etc. While it can be a worthy distraction it would have been nice to be able to quest with other players. Especially with those difficult missions (high level photos, gold star ratings, etc.). There remains the issue of connected players to a host server being unable to unlock new landmarks/outposts, etc. I personally never join a server if I play multiplayer as I always want the option, so I host. It explains why there are so many servers with just 1 player in them.My issue is that this developer seems to be following the trend. A console release has been announced recently and with the lack of updates it will only get worse in my opinion. A guise of two separate console and PC development teams is their only defense - just take a look at the patch note comments. The sad truth is that development for the PC version will slow until they get their cash flow from the console release. The game takes a modestly beefy PC to render the graphics at their ultimate potential, and a lot of people don't have the pcmasterrace in them.  If they get a console version that runs at 30 FPS and has full game pad support, a lot of people might hop on that boat. Why wouldn't they release a console version? Lotta money potential. And that seems to be their game - hey, it's a business.6.5/10"
